244
00:16:48,663 --> 00:16:50,541
I just did it because
some book told me to.

245
00:16:50,744 --> 00:16:53,133
- What am I, gonna be in Swan Lake?
- Why not?

246
00:16:53,344 --> 00:16:56,382
You see stories like that on the news
all the time. It's inspiring.

247
00:16:56,585 --> 00:17:00,055
It's depressing. It seems so desperate.

248
00:17:00,265 --> 00:17:02,142
Maybe it's a little desperate.

249
00:17:03,346 --> 00:17:06,418
Besides, who knows?

250
00:17:06,946 --> 00:17:10,576
It's always possible
you might meet a man.

251
00:17:10,787 --> 00:17:14,177
That part of my life is over.

252
00:17:16,028 --> 00:17:18,906
You're supposed to flip this mattress
every two months.

253
00:17:20,629 --> 00:17:22,142
I do mine every 14 weeks.

254
00:17:22,349 --> 00:17:26,582
Well, I can't remember ever flipping this.
It's probably been 20 years.

255
00:17:26,790 --> 00:17:28,109
Come on, get up.

256
00:17:28,510 --> 00:17:31,946
You haven't finished going
through Nathaniel's clothes.

257
00:17:34,391 --> 00:17:36,347
Ruth.

258
00:17:36,591 --> 00:17:39,060
Ruth, how can I help you?

259
00:17:39,272 --> 00:17:42,264
You can lift this up with me.

260
00:17:43,992 --> 00:17:46,109
An uncovered mattress is so sad.

261
00:17:46,313 --> 00:17:48,986
Help me turn this over!

262
00:17:49,913 --> 00:17:51,870
All right.

263
00:17:52,834 --> 00:17:54,665
Okay.

264
00:17:59,555 --> 00:18:01,386
All right.

265
00:18:07,756 --> 00:18:10,225
Does it feel any different?

266
00:18:10,437 --> 00:18:12,268
No.

267
00:18:19,998 --> 00:18:21,876
Save our park!

268
00:18:22,079 --> 00:18:26,118
Save our park!
Save our park!

269
00:18:26,319 --> 00:18:30,359
Save our park!
Save our park!

270
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:34,474
No more money for politicians!
Money for parks!

271
00:18:34,681 --> 00:18:36,478
Save our park!
Save our park!

272
00:19:01,445 --> 00:19:04,040
What are you doing?

273
00:19:04,326 --> 00:19:07,682
You have a gift.
You can help people.

274
00:19:11,887 --> 00:19:13,036
Fine.

275
00:19:13,247 --> 00:19:15,842
Go back to peddling soy milk
and nailing waitresses.

276
00:19:16,048 --> 00:19:17,925
What do I care? I'm dead.

277
00:19:21,049 --> 00:19:22,243
Move it, asshole!

278
00:19:23,009 --> 00:19:28,084
Save our park!
Save our park!

279
00:19:28,370 --> 00:19:29,803
So now you don't want to sell.

280
00:19:30,570 --> 00:19:33,005
- I know it sounds crazy.
- No, not at all.

281
00:19:33,211 --> 00:19:36,726
We'll keep the business for the rest of
the day, then sell it again tomorrow.

282
00:19:36,931 --> 00:19:38,603
- Hear me out.
- This is a good system.

283
00:19:38,811 --> 00:19:41,201
We'll sell in the mornings,
keep it in the afternoons.

284
00:19:41,412 --> 00:19:44,563
Sometimes, we sell again in the evenings
when we can't make a decision.

285
00:19:44,772 --> 00:19:46,570
David, you're not being fair.

286
00:19:46,773 --> 00:19:49,128
When I didn't want to sell,
you could've cared less.

287
00:19:49,333 --> 00:19:50,686
When Nate doesn't, you listen.

288
00:19:50,893 --> 00:19:55,649
Okay, I'm a terrible mother, who's
responsible for all your problems. Happy?

289
00:19:58,215 --> 00:20:01,366
So you had some revelation, and
now you wanna be a funeral director?

290
00:20:01,575 --> 00:20:04,329
- How long is that going to last?
- He does have a point, Nate.

291
00:20:04,616 --> 00:20:07,688
- You don't always stick with things.
- You can't be in the same room...

292
00:20:07,896 --> 00:20:08,851
...with a dead body.

293
00:20:09,137 --> 00:20:12,095
I know, but there's a reason for that.

294
00:20:12,857 --> 00:20:15,656
This is what I'm supposed to do.

295
00:20:15,858 --> 00:20:18,452
Which is why I've spent so much time
running away from it.

296
00:20:28,340 --> 00:20:30,695
My whole life, I've been a tourist.

297
00:20:30,900 --> 00:20:34,052
Now I have the chance to do some
good instead of just sucking up air.

298
00:20:34,781 --> 00:20:39,138
I know it's a lot to ask of you, I know,
but I just really think that we can do this.

299
00:20:39,422 --> 00:20:41,697
You and me, together.

300
00:20:42,262 --> 00:20:44,059
Brothers.

301
00:20:44,262 --> 00:20:46,333
Like we used to be.

302
00:20:50,423 --> 00:20:53,222
We could still sell to Kroehner
and both manage Fisher & Sons.

303
00:20:53,424 --> 00:20:55,654
Yeah, but then we're just
spokesmodels...

304
00:20:55,864 --> 00:20:58,538
...working to make fat Republican
stockholders richer.

305
00:20:58,745 --> 00:21:01,054
Kroehner doesn't give a shit
about people. We care.

306
00:21:01,265 --> 00:21:05,100
- We can help them through their grief.
- This is a business, Nate, not a charity.

307
00:21:05,306 --> 00:21:07,695
Of course it's a business, but...

308
00:21:07,906 --> 00:21:09,898
...it's more than that, and you know it.

309
00:21:16,868 --> 00:21:18,062
Okay.

310
00:21:18,268 --> 00:21:19,496
Great.

311
00:21:19,948 --> 00:21:22,907
I'll call Gilardi and tell him
he can kiss our collective ass.

312
00:21:23,109 --> 00:21:24,383
Language.

313
00:21:25,589 --> 00:21:28,388
Maybe Dad knew what he was doing.

314
00:21:35,071 --> 00:21:37,107
You did not have to waste this stuff
on me.

315
00:21:37,311 --> 00:21:39,302
Oh, please. My parents got a case of it...

316
00:21:39,512 --> 00:21:43,744
...from some TV movie they
were technical advisors on.

317
00:21:43,952 --> 00:21:46,103
Some serial-killer thing for cable.

318
00:21:46,313 --> 00:21:49,385
Oh, they're such whores.
They'll do anything.

319
00:21:49,593 --> 00:21:50,867
Gosh.

320
00:21:51,073 --> 00:21:54,032
Can you believe this
stuff is expensive?

321
00:21:55,994 --> 00:21:59,271
You know, I've always wanted to tell off
some corporate suit, some...

322
00:21:59,475 --> 00:22:02,547
...greedy little
Nazi fuck, you know?

323
00:22:03,556 --> 00:22:04,909
That's very hostile.

324
00:22:05,116 --> 00:22:08,825
No, I was very diplomatic. I just said,
"Thanks, but we changed our minds."

325
00:22:09,036 --> 00:22:11,232
What did he do?

326
00:22:11,437 --> 00:22:13,587
He didn't do anything.
What's he gonna do?

327
00:22:13,877 --> 00:22:17,154
- This is completely unacceptable.
- The Baxters changed their mind.

328
00:22:17,358 --> 00:22:21,397
- They're going with the Unger Mortuary.
- Was there a reason?

329
00:22:23,159 --> 00:22:25,229
They probably just underbid you.

330
00:22:25,439 --> 00:22:27,111
Hal Unger never underbid anybody.

331
00:22:27,319 --> 00:22:30,312
He moved to Florida. They were
bought out by Kroehner months ago.

332
00:22:30,520 --> 00:22:32,397
Sign here.

333
00:22:34,521 --> 00:22:36,079
You know...

334
00:22:36,281 --> 00:22:40,355
...I didn't just decide to stay in
Los Angeles because of the business.

335
00:22:40,562 --> 00:22:43,554
- I had another reason.
- Oh, please. Don't ruin this.

336
00:22:43,762 --> 00:22:47,438
- I've got such a nice buzz going.
- It was you.

337
00:22:48,483 --> 00:22:49,518
Nate, get serious.

338
00:22:49,723 --> 00:22:51,760
- It's true.
- No, it's not.

339
00:22:51,964 --> 00:22:54,842
You're staying here because
you found something you want to do.

340
00:22:55,044 --> 00:22:59,914
I am the extra bonus
that probably won't work out.

341
00:23:00,125 --> 00:23:03,435
Sometimes your honesty
gets really tiresome.

342
00:23:03,725 --> 00:23:07,514
- I don't want any children.
- Who said anything about children?

343
00:23:07,726 --> 00:23:09,877
I was referring to you.

344
00:23:10,087 --> 00:23:12,362
I got something for you.

345
00:23:23,889 --> 00:23:25,880
Open it.

346
00:23:28,890 --> 00:23:32,041
Glenn Miller Orchestra
at the Hollywood Palladium.

347
00:23:32,250 --> 00:23:35,049
Brenda, this is so cool.
I've never been to the Palladium.

348
00:23:35,251 --> 00:23:38,607
You grew up in L.A., and you've never
been to the Palladium? Pathetic.

349
00:23:41,172 --> 00:23:43,766
These are for three weeks from now.

350
00:23:43,972 --> 00:23:46,248
How'd you know
I wouldn't be in Seattle?

351
00:23:46,453 --> 00:23:48,409
I didn't.

352
00:24:36,141 --> 00:24:37,574
Morning, Rico.

353
00:24:38,541 --> 00:24:41,102
Just what I need, another boss
breathing down my neck.

354
00:24:41,302 --> 00:24:43,133
Put me to work.

355
00:24:46,743 --> 00:24:48,699
Hello?

356
00:25:03,505 --> 00:25:06,896
Pregnancy's kicked Vanessa's hormones
into overload. I gotta talk her down.

357
00:25:07,106 --> 00:25:10,497
If you wanna help, take Mr. Romano
out of the bag and put him on the table.

358
00:25:10,707 --> 00:25:14,063
Remember, breathe through
your mouth, man. He's pretty ripe.

359
00:25:40,632 --> 00:25:42,827
Oh, Christ.

360
00:25:49,993 --> 00:25:52,029
- Nate.
- Great, look what you made me do.

361
00:25:52,233 --> 00:25:54,873
Oh, gross.

362
00:25:56,114 --> 00:25:58,993
I want to talk to you
about something.

363
00:25:59,195 --> 00:26:04,953
I don't know if you noticed, but I'm
a little busy swimming in a man's guts.

364
00:26:07,916 --> 00:26:09,474
I don't know what this is.

365
00:26:09,676 --> 00:26:14,228
I'm picking up a part of a person,
and I don't even know what part it is!

366
00:26:14,437 --> 00:26:17,714
Fine, I'll talk to you later.

367
00:26:17,918 --> 00:26:18,873
Oh, God.

368
00:26:26,479 --> 00:26:27,878
Sorry.

369
00:26:39,281 --> 00:26:41,273
What the hell are you doing?

370
00:26:41,482 --> 00:26:44,280
I work here now.
I have to be a part of things.

371
00:26:44,482 --> 00:26:47,316
Let Rico take care of him.

372
00:26:47,523 --> 00:26:52,358
I have a job for you that's much better
suited to your particular talents.

373
00:27:04,365 --> 00:27:08,598
Morning, Nate.
Lovely day, isn't it?

374
00:27:08,806 --> 00:27:10,957
I've seen better.

375
00:27:11,247 --> 00:27:14,603
I only wanted to say hello,
seeing that I'm your new neighbor.

376
00:27:16,607 --> 00:27:19,884
We just bought that house
across the street.

377
00:27:21,648 --> 00:27:23,480
Got it for a song too.

378
00:27:23,769 --> 00:27:28,240
Oh, and by the way, we're planning to
put you out of business in six months.

379
00:27:28,609 --> 00:27:31,329
They're opening a Poseidon Society
across the street?

380
00:27:31,530 --> 00:27:33,327
That's right.

381
00:27:33,530 --> 00:27:35,761
What is a Poseidon Society?

382
00:27:35,971 --> 00:27:39,680
They sell cremations, cheap cremations.
Now, for a fraction of what we charge...

383
00:27:39,891 --> 00:27:42,690
...you can dump off the relative
you never really liked...

384
00:27:42,892 --> 00:27:45,406
...at the Torch Mart across the street.

385
00:27:45,612 --> 00:27:48,525
I guess we have to just
continue to do our best.

386
00:27:49,653 --> 00:27:51,291
And how exactly do we do that?

387
00:27:51,493 --> 00:27:53,769
You know Lou the florist,
that sweet old guy?

388
00:27:53,974 --> 00:27:56,727
He just upped what
he charges us by 200 percent.

389
00:27:57,054 --> 00:27:59,694
And that chemical dealer
on Figueroa is now suing us...

390
00:27:59,895 --> 00:28:02,967
...over some nonexistent
shipment of cavity fluid.

391
00:28:03,175 --> 00:28:05,895
Every other supplier that we have
in common with Kroehner...

392
00:28:06,176 --> 00:28:08,929
...suddenly developed
some problem with Fisher & Sons.

393
00:28:09,136 --> 00:28:11,013
For some reason,
by the name of Kroehner...

394
00:28:11,217 --> 00:28:13,811
...the Health Department
is going to inspect us next week.

395
00:28:14,017 --> 00:28:16,372
Yeah, so what? Isn't everything clean?

396
00:28:16,657 --> 00:28:20,731
Yes, but any inspection means
we have to update something.

397
00:28:20,938 --> 00:28:24,409
If it's the ventilation system, we're sunk.

398
00:28:24,699 --> 00:28:27,532
We should've sold.

399
00:28:27,739 --> 00:28:30,891
Nate? I'm having a problem.

400
00:28:31,300 --> 00:28:34,372
You don't happen to have
Mr. Romano's foot on you, do you?

401
00:28:37,781 --> 00:28:40,011
Do you remember picking up the foot?

402
00:28:40,221 --> 00:28:44,374
I think so, but my eyes were shut,
and I was trying not to vomit.

403
00:28:44,582 --> 00:28:46,971
I'm not happy.

404
00:28:48,263 --> 00:28:51,335
Well, that's very interesting, David,
because I'm ecstatic.

405
00:28:53,303 --> 00:28:55,454
Maybe the morgue
never gave us that foot.

406
00:28:56,424 --> 00:28:58,380
Both feet are listed
in the paperwork, Nate.

407
00:28:58,584 --> 00:29:01,736
Just think, Nate. Is there
any other point you could've lost it?

408
00:29:01,945 --> 00:29:03,936
- Lost what?
- Nothing.

409
00:29:04,145 --> 00:29:07,695
If you lost something, look under the
bed. That's where things always turn up.

410
00:29:07,906 --> 00:29:11,057
- I doubt that applies in this case.
- That's what people always say...

411
00:29:11,266 --> 00:29:13,906
...then they find what they're
looking for under the bed.

412
00:29:14,107 --> 00:29:17,623
- Mom, we're really busy down here.
- The upstairs machine is broken.

413
00:29:17,828 --> 00:29:19,307
I called the repairman but...

414
00:29:19,508 --> 00:29:22,386
Oh, my God, what is this?

415
00:29:23,228 --> 00:29:29,418
Someone left a Kleenex in their pocket,
and now it's all over everything.

416
00:29:30,190 --> 00:29:32,658
It's disgusting.

417
00:29:36,391 --> 00:29:38,461
Nate, retrace your steps.

418
00:29:38,671 --> 00:29:41,789
Is there any other point
you could've lost the foot?

419
00:29:42,472 --> 00:29:45,669
I almost dropped him at the morgue,
but the bag didn't open.

420
00:29:45,952 --> 00:29:49,866
I tripped on the stairs,
but nothing fell out.

421
00:29:50,153 --> 00:29:52,508
Banged into the freezer.
Spilled him onto the floor...

422
00:29:52,713 --> 00:29:56,423
- And I picked him up from off the floor.
- It should be here.

423
00:29:57,354 --> 00:30:01,109
I'd say it's an $8 million lawsuit.

424
00:30:01,755 --> 00:30:03,711
At least.

425
00:30:13,477 --> 00:30:16,037
- Here she comes.
- Like my new shoes? They're size 12.

426
00:30:16,237 --> 00:30:17,306
Toe slut.

427
00:31:04,965 --> 00:31:06,638
Amelia?

428
00:31:06,846 --> 00:31:09,485
It's me, Ruth.

429
00:31:09,686 --> 00:31:13,316
Your best friend needs help.

430
00:31:27,529 --> 00:31:29,281
Is he all put together?

431
00:31:29,569 --> 00:31:33,279
- Oh, he's 100 percent there.
- Absolutely.

432
00:31:33,570 --> 00:31:34,719
I'd like to see him.

433
00:31:37,331 --> 00:31:41,370
I'm sorry, our embalmer
is a little on the artistic side.

434
00:31:41,571 --> 00:31:44,245
He gets crazy if he has any input.

435
00:31:44,452 --> 00:31:46,602
It's best to wait until
we're completely done.

436
00:31:47,532 --> 00:31:49,603
One more thing.

437
00:31:49,813 --> 00:31:51,166
His shoes.

438
00:31:53,133 --> 00:31:55,853
- What are you, an idiot?
- Those are his favorite shoes.

439
00:31:56,054 --> 00:31:59,729
He has perfectly comfortable loafers,
which would be much more appropriate.

440
00:31:59,934 --> 00:32:04,850
Yes, I myself have loafers
which are just like walking on air.

441
00:32:06,055 --> 00:32:07,694
We should've just
told her the truth.

442
00:32:08,256 --> 00:32:12,535
"Sorry, Mrs. Romano, but my idiot
of a brother lost a part of your husband."

443
00:32:12,737 --> 00:32:14,693
Yeah, that would've worked.

444
00:32:14,897 --> 00:32:16,091
Where are you going?

445
00:32:16,297 --> 00:32:17,776
I have someplace I have to be.

446
00:32:17,977 --> 00:32:20,776
When I return, I hope to
be greeted by a foot...

447
00:32:20,978 --> 00:32:23,936
...a solution as to how to stop
a billion-dollar corporation...

448
00:32:24,138 --> 00:32:28,291
...from putting us out of business
and pruned hedges.

449
00:32:32,700 --> 00:32:36,090
- Aren't you glad you're out of the house?
- Yes, this is just what I needed.

450
00:32:36,301 --> 00:32:38,417
We should try and get a seat
right in front.

451
00:32:38,621 --> 00:32:42,296
- I'm placing a bet.
- We should just try and enjoy the day.

452
00:32:42,502 --> 00:32:45,892
I don't see why we need to gamble.

453
00:32:48,703 --> 00:32:49,897
That's sweet.

454
00:32:51,143 --> 00:32:53,373
You both look so happy.

455
00:32:53,583 --> 00:32:55,575
It's just an act.

456
00:32:56,424 --> 00:32:59,860
Just enjoy it while it lasts,
which isn't very long.

457
00:33:00,384 --> 00:33:01,454
Excuse me?

458
00:33:01,665 --> 00:33:04,577
You think you have forever,
but you don't.

459
00:33:04,785 --> 00:33:06,936
Soon you start to get on each
other's nerves...

460
00:33:07,866 --> 00:33:10,699
...then you don't tell the other person
as much as you used to.

461
00:33:10,906 --> 00:33:13,467
What's the point?
You thought they understood you.

462
00:33:13,667 --> 00:33:15,464
- But they never did, not really.
- Ruth.

463
00:33:15,667 --> 00:33:18,181
Finally, not only do you not
tell him anything real...

464
00:33:18,387 --> 00:33:19,980
...you actively start lying to him.

465
00:33:21,028 --> 00:33:23,781
Then when you think it can't get
any worse, he up and dies.

466
00:33:24,829 --> 00:33:30,222
- I think I see a shorter line over there.
- Bye.

467
00:33:30,950 --> 00:33:33,066
No matter what you do,
you end up alone!

468
00:33:33,270 --> 00:33:35,864
Not knowing who you are
or what you really want!

469
00:33:36,070 --> 00:33:40,030
Ruth, Ruth, why did we
come here today?

470
00:33:40,511 --> 00:33:43,982
To have fun. Aren't you having fun?

471
00:33:46,192 --> 00:33:48,387
I think it's wobbling.

472
00:33:48,592 --> 00:33:52,381
It just looks like it's wobbling because
you've been staring at it for so long.

473
00:33:52,593 --> 00:33:54,664
It's definitely wobbling.

474
00:33:54,874 --> 00:33:56,626
You're hallucinating.

475
00:33:56,834 --> 00:33:57,789
Life is strange.

476
00:33:57,994 --> 00:34:00,873
If one of those tiny screws
isn't screwed on tight enough...

477
00:34:01,075 --> 00:34:04,067
...that thing could fall
and kill us instantaneously.

478
00:34:04,275 --> 00:34:06,870
Just chop us to bits like a Cuisinart.

479
00:34:09,156 --> 00:34:12,307
And an assassin with a semiautomatic
could walk through the door...

480
00:34:12,516 --> 00:34:16,066
...and spray our brains all over the place.

481
00:34:16,277 --> 00:34:21,636
The sun could become a supernova
and engulf the entire planet in flames.

482
00:34:25,599 --> 00:34:27,715
David Fisher.

483
00:34:27,999 --> 00:34:30,638
We just got a call from Claire's school.
She's in trouble.

484
00:34:31,320 --> 00:34:34,232
- Can't Mom handle this?
